Secrets Handling
Containers must not embed or persist sensitive information at any stage of the image lifecycle. Secrets must be managed securely and injected only at runtime.
Never bake secrets into container images
Sensitive data such as passwords, API keys, certificates, or tokens must not be included in Dockerfiles, image layers, or application code. Embedding secrets in images creates irreversible exposure risk.
Avoid long-lived credentials in environment variables
Environment variables are not considered a secure storage mechanism, as they can be exposed through logs, debugging tools, or process inspection. Only short-lived, dynamically generated credentials may be used where strictly necessary.
Use centralized secret management with HashiCorp Vault
All secrets (passwords, keys, certificates) must be stored, managed, and accessed through Vault. Vault provides secure storage, access control, auditing, and dynamic secret generation.
Do not rely on platform-native secret stores as a source of truth
Mechanisms such as OpenShift or Kubernetes Secrets are not sufficient as primary secret management solutions. They may only be used as transient delivery mechanisms when backed by Vault.
Proper secret handling reduces the risk of credential leakage, strengthens auditability, and ensures compliance with enterprise security requirements.
Stateless and Disposable Containers
Containers must be designed as ephemeral, replaceable units with no dependency on local state.
Containers must be stateless
Application state must be stored externally (e.g., databases, object storage, or managed services). Containers should not retain or depend on in-memory or filesystem state across restarts.
No reliance on local filesystem persistence
Data written to the container filesystem is non-durable and must not be required for application continuity. Any required persistence must be handled outside the container.
Design for disposability and rapid recovery
Containers must be easily replaceable without manual intervention. Workloads should tolerate restarts, rescheduling, and scaling without impacting functionality.
Ensure fast startup and graceful shutdown
Containers should initialize quickly and handle termination signals correctly, allowing for clean shutdown within defined time constraints.
Designing containers as stateless and disposable improves scalability, resilience, and operational consistency across environments.


